Everyone knows of the Nutcracker and most of us have probably seen some version of the ballet, whether in person or on television. You might also know that there are different variations of the Nutcracker.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
But do any of us really know the story of the Nutcracker? ​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
I thought I did. I’ve always loved the Nutcracker. I’ve seen the ballet. But this year, I went down a Nutcracker rabbit hole and discovered that there is so much I didn’t know.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
Stay tuned this month as I share my Nutcracker journey.

But the more I began walking through our home, making intentional choices about what to hang on the walls or place on the shelves, the more I grabbed for my cute little tool kit. Hang a family photo here. Snip a loose thread there. Measure the wall space over there for a potential new piece of furniture. ​​​​​​​​

This little bag is helping me curate a home that not only makes me happy, but welcomes those I hold dear.

Registration is open for February's Home Meets Heart Workshop! Next Friday, we'll build upon the ideas and values we explored in HEART and begin to use them to create intentional spaces that bring us joy.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
An example of something we'll cover: If family is the value you are trying to highlight within your home, some tangible ways you can incorporate this value are a spacious living room with comfortable seating, a large dining table for family meals, and a cozy kitchen where everyone can gather. You might also incorporate family photos and other sentimental items to make your home feel more personal and connected to your family's history.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
This workshop combines my love of living an intentional life with creating a beautiful space in which to spend time with your loved ones.​​​​​​​​

We've had some great questions about the new Undated Week on One Page Planner! While we work to put together a video to show you the details in more depth, here is a quick run-down of the changes...⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
1. The format is the same– each tabbed section has a HEART Check-in, a monthly spread, and weekly pages.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
2. We've removed the months from the tabs⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
3. We've removed the dates from the monthly and weekly spreads.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
4. The cover is removable. This allows you to purchase just the inside planner to keep a favorite cover or to buy a new cover for your current planner⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
5. We include monthly planning stickers with dates and holiday icons ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Why did we do this? Flexibility! ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I've always said Different Seasons call for Different Systems. Some months I need my Day on One Page to keep me organized. Some months I don't need my planner at all! ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
By removing the months and dates from this planner, I can utilize the planner in how it benefits me most— no more unused pages. Or, if I need more room for notes and lists, I can turn the page and remain on track for that month.

Tomorrow begins our celebration of our 1-year Book-a-versary of A More Beautiful Life. As we approach this milestone, I've been reminded of all the tools I've created over the years to help others apply the HEART GOALS™️ framework to their own lives. One of the ways I'm most excited to celebrate this book-a-versary is with a book club! Over the course of 5 weeks, beginning May 15th, we'll be digging into my book and going through a HEART Check-in together. The book club will be happening in my membership community, Style & Story (which is opening to new members for just one week, starting May 8th! Sign up to be notified from the link in my bio). We'll read a few chapters a week, discuss what we're reading, and begin to get back on track with our HEART Goals as we get ready for summer. And there will be an opportunity to submit questions to Whitney for a Q&A session all about the book!

If you still need to get a copy of the book, order during our book-a-versary celebration May 1-May 7 and get a free Day on One Page planner!

Next week we kick-off our weekly Book Club discussion of my book, A More Beautiful Life. If you've ever been curious about the Monthly HEART Check-in pages in your planner, this is a great way to begin the practice of reflecting each month on how to continually move towards setting goals for your life using the HEART framework. ​​​​​​​​​
In my membership group, Style & Story, we'll be breaking down the book into weekly sections starting May 15th to give ourselves the much-needed HEART Check-in before we move into the next season of life.

Will you be joining us? Doors to Style & Story open tomorrow!

We live in a culture that values productivity and accomplishment, often at the expense of our own well-being. We’re told that we need to hustle, grind, and work around the clock if we want to succeed. But what if I told you that saying “no” could be one of the most powerful tools in your arsenal for achieving your goals? By setting boundaries and protecting your time and energy, you can focus on what really matters and make the most of your precious resources.​​​​​​​​​

Yes, I selfied myself at the library while waiting for my kids to pick out books, just to tell you thank you. When I woke up at 4 am, unable to sleep, I realized 19 of you had left encouraging comments, and five more of you had dm’d. A compilation of favorite advice offered: get over your ego. Just show up. Be yourself. Don’t worry about what people will think. Be here, be consistent.

Ok, I’ll try.

And thank you.

Our poor dining room floor, y’all. This is NOT where you want to spend your hard-earned dollars. We LOVE this house (never moving) but I am pretty sure the plumbing has NEVER worked right. It started backing up a month after we moved in. We thoroughly frustrated one plumber before we realized it was the septic system. (🤢💸) Then it started backing up again. We hacked into our new dining room floors and replaced a portion of sewer line. (🤢💸) Backed up again. Kitchen floor this time, and we discovered a pile of concrete had been dumped on the sewer line 50 years ago, messing up the fall angle. (🤢💸) And then it backed up again. There is only one section of the line that had not been replaced. Plumber Blake worked his tail off to replace it while we were out of town a couple of weeks ago. We LOVE plumber Blake, but it was still 🤢💸. And now to repair and refinish the floor for the third time since purchasing the house.

Fun, yeah?

Woke up this morning and had no idea how this table was going to come together. I kept telling myself “just channel @changnatalie - WWNC do? What does this look like? This is easy. A party and a trade show are basically the same thing, right?”

We did it, y’all. 

Three weeks ago, my BFFF asked me to host a dinner party. David made the table this week. We hung the draperies, detailed the drywall, bleached the sofa, fluffed the pillows, polished the silver, made the playlist, power washed the patio, cut down dead limbs, dug out the linens, the amber glasses, bamboo flatware, rattan napkin rings. We swept, dusted, scrubbed, pruned, and tidied, at all hours and on all days for two weeks. Three weeks of yard work, ten bags of mulch, one thousand and fourteen weeds pulled. Don’t ask me how we did it. It took prayer, two planners, one notepad, and some gut instinct. 

But we pulled it off and 10 dear old friends showed up and God showed off with a miraculous 80 degree day in the middle of an Oklahoma summer, all for a night under the stars. They brought the best wine and dessert, assembled the salad and buttered the bread and made the iced tea, and we laughed hard, in a way that only the oldest friends can do. 

There’s no such thing as perfect, except it was.

In the frosty chill of this past January, I embarked on a significant journey. A journey that involved a departure from my well-trodden paths and a step into a brave new world. Yes, you guessed it right! I made the switch from iCal to Google Calendar. It may seem like an insignificant change to some, but for someone who has clung to iCal and paper planners with a determination that rivals my grip on the last cupcake at a party, it was monumental.​​​​​​​​​
Armed with the Navy Seal mantra, "Slow is smooth and smooth is fast," I prepared myself for this transition. The mission was clear: I needed to find a way to streamline my schedule, which was expanding and contracting with the unpredictable ebb and flow of after-school activities, multiple doctor appointments, and life in general.

Read more on my Substack where you'll find a tutorial on how I integrated an online calendar with my paper planner.
